ollection of correspondence between Bachmann and Celan enables new scholarly engagement with both authors. It elucidates the complex connections between their personal histories and poetry, shedding light on the ways they found literary expression for their experiences with totalitarianism. In addition, the letters are poetic texts in their own right, to be read in the context of the poets’ works as a whole.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aBachmann, Ingeborg. 4aCelan, Paul. 4aErinnerungskultur. 4aNachkriegslyrik. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aBachmann, Ingeborg.  aCelan, Paul.  aCulture of remembrance.  aPost-war poetry.1 aBöschenstein, Bernhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarr, Ruven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaeding, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReimer, Madlen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRenker, Cindy K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchuster, Marc-Oliver, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStoll, Mareike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUžukauskaitė, Lina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeigel, Sigrid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWiedemann, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWimmer, Gernot, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWimmer, Gernot, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Literary and Cultural Studies 2000 - 2014z9783110637854oZDB-23-GLC08iTitle is part of 